Maybe we can be romantic while also be diligent of our surroundings and circumstances that we are bound to, or maybe we never could due to the error of our humanity... At least we can keep trying.

Title: Of Mice and Men
Author: John Steinbeck
My Review: Being from Los Angeles and having encountered a multitude of superficial people throughout my life, I found this book to be a strikingly accurate depiction of the fragility of friendship and the opportunistic circumstances that can arise when one isn’t careful. Through this simple yet profound tale, Steinbeck reminds us of the beauty and tragedy in the aspirations we hold onto, even when the odds are stacked against us. At its core, it’s the delicate nature of human connection and the elusive promise of the American Dream that binds George and Lennie, making their story feel deeply human and heartbreakingly real.

Title: The 7 Habits of Highly Effective People: Powerful Lessons in Personal Change
Author: Stephen R. Covey
My Review: A transformative guide to personal and professional growth, offering a structured framework for becoming more intentional in life. Covey’s approach isn’t just about productivity but also building character and aligning actions with values. The habits themselves are a simple roadmap for meaningful collaboration. Be Proactive encourages us to take ownership of our choices rather than reacting to circumstances. Begin with the End in Mind helps us define as well as align our actions with long-term goals. Put First Things First emphasizes prioritizing what truly matters so that you could essentially train your executive functioning.  Turning outward, Think Win-Win fosters mutual respect and benefit in relationships, while Seek First to Understand, Then to Be Understood challenges us to listen empathetically before asserting our perspectives. Synergize is the celebration of teamwork and the creative potential of diverse perspectives and backgrounds, and finally, Sharpen the Saw reminds us to continually renew ourselves: physically, mentally, emotionally, and spiritually. Each of the following habits build upon each other causing somewhat of a snowball effect on one's quality of life (ideally). The insights I find are timeless, and while the concepts take effort to implement and work on every day, overall this is informative for how to live a fulfilled life.

Author: Robert Frost
George Orwell
My Review: A stark reminder about how language (banned or taboo words change in meaning e.g. 'nature'), history (US education system bias), and even thought itself (cancel culture / social media hive mind) can be weaponized to maintain control of it's people, similar to how the bipartisan system in the US divides as an us vs them mentality time and time again.

Title: Catcher in the Rye
Author: J.D. Salinger
My Review: Having read this while I was teenager, I was very cynical and "edgy". Upon reading this, I realized that beneath the sarcasm and angst lies a vulnerable longing to protect innocence in a world that seems intent on crushing it. I did not discover the world is a cruel place, rather, that the world is far more complex to navigate than I originally believed it to be and that the only solution was to simply accept the novel and unknown no matter how much I tried to prepare, understand, and plan my life out for. By reading this, no matter what stage in life, hopefully you could relate to Holden.

Title: American Born Chinese
Author: Gene Luen Yang
My Review: Using elements of Chinese mythology to reflect struggles of assimilation and self acceptance in a way that feels universal yet intimately specific. I could only feel sympathy and ask how we reconcile the many aspects of who we are when the world insists on simplifying culture for it's convenience?

Title: Sir Gawain and the Green Knight (Penguin Classics)
Author: Anonymous
My Review: The following could be taken as a meditation on the fragile interplay between chivalric pride and mortal frailty. If the knight’s lofty code can illuminate the path to honor, it can just as well cast deep shadows of doubt across the human conscience. It also unveils an enduring tension between individual virtue and the obligations imposed by courtly society a notion that resonated for centuries (from my understanding) of literary tradition.

Title: The Communist Manifesto
Author: Karl Marx
Additional Authors: Friedrich Engels, Samuel Moore, Gareth Stedman Jones
My Review: One might read it as a radical extension of Enlightenment thought, if human reason can light the path to self determination, it could just as well shine a path to a new social order. Yet, it also hints at the deep-rooted tensions between individual autonomy and collective will. A tension displayed in every western world society. We should therefore still ask (no matter what you believe in politically) who truly holds power over our lives, and how much of our fate do we surrender when we accept social structures as inevitable?

Title: Metamorphosis and Other Stories
Author: Franz Kafka
My Review: An unsettling yet captivating journey into the absurd and the existential. Kafka’s writing masterfully captures the alienation of modern life, with his characters often trapped in incomprehensible circumstances that reflect our own quiet fears and frustrations. Though a very difficult read for me personally, I could see how Kafka holds a mirror to the fragmented human condition in each story, crafting narratives that are both haunting and deeply thought-provoking. The bizarre plots are challenging to wrap your head around, but that’s part of their lasting impact. Hopefully, one day I’ll better understand the layers of meaning Kafka was exploring in his surreal and enigmatic worlds.

Title: Cracking the Coding Interview: 189 Programming Questions and Solutions
Author: Gayle Laakmann McDowell
My Review: I read this book while preparing for technical interviews, and it proved to be an invaluable resource. The majority of the examples are in Java, which was particularly useful at the time since I was focusing on that language. Although I’ve since transitioned mostly to Python, I still found the discussions on data structures, algorithms, Big O notation, and the extensive practice problems highly relevant. The content is presented at a pace that feels approachable yet thorough.

Title: Perfume: The Story of a Murderer
Author: Patrick Süskind

Title: Lord of the Flies
Author: William Golding
My Review:
This isn’t just about 'human nature' or how 'man turns to beast as time passes by on a deserted island.' It’s a testament to a certain type of mentality. For example, if we replaced the children from England with a group of stranded kids from Nepal, the outcome would be entirely different. Why is that? Because Nepal is an example of a country that derives happiness from community, making it far easier for individuals to assimilate and work together.

This isn’t to say, 'Ooh, capitalism bad'no, because capitalism can bring about wonders that help most if done properly and within reason. What I am suggesting is that individualism should not be celebrated as heavily as it is in today’s world. The genius of this story lies in its ability to make the descent into chaos feel both inevitable and terrifyingly familiar for anyone with this mentality, succumbing without rules on a deserted island.

I implore you, including myself to do things because they help others. Simple and obvious but it is nice to remember and a situation like Lord of the Flies, even if hypothetical might not even happen.

Title: To Kill a Mockingbird
Author: Harper Lee
My Review: I wonder why this book is so popular to teach in middle school. I find it ironic that, during a paramount moment in development, in a setting where compliance is crucial, we are required to read a book that asks us to confront our own complicity in systems of injustice and to do the right thing, even when it is illegal or socially unacceptable. Last I checked, the compliance instilled in school often translates to working for a company that may be morally bankrupt. How does one cope with this notion for the rest of their days in such a hypothetical situation?

Title: Mum dreams about a Little Lightning Bug (Books about the Little Lightning Bug's Journey)
Author: Judit Franch

Title: Brave New World
Author: Aldous Huxley
My Review: We believe we have so much free will when we don't whether we know it or not. This dystopian fiction demonstrates that very clearly no matter how much autonomy we believe we have, the greater forces above usually have say on what we see, eat, consume, therefore echoes into what we say, create, and demonstrate.

Title: How to Win Friends and Influence People
Author: Dale Carnegie
My Review: It is one thing to gamify conversation in order to have the "ball in your court", it is another to take from this book the simple lesson of being genuinely interested in others will spur about amazing and lasting connections. What good is it that we have conversation with someone when all we want to do is hear ourselves? The key "strategies" listed in this book can come about from mere intuition of a neurotypical person for example. This is not to take away from what the book teaches however, because we all start somewhere, (especially due to the confines of social media and the rise of para-social relationships) I find this to be a reminder of what we might potentially lose more of in the future: connection.

Title: Man's Search for Meaning
Author: Viktor E. Frankl
Additional Authors: Harold S. Kushner, William J. Winslade
My Review: To think that we are actively engaging in our pursuit of happiness when in reality it comes to us naturally is a simple message. But to the extent of the context of this book takes on a different meaning entirely. How could so much suffering surrounding you allow for you to even move forward with your thoughts. Being reminded daily of the trials and tribulations in a concentration camp just to transform the plethora of emotions that one could have into one of helping others cope with their own emotions is to say the least inspiring and am forever grateful having read this book.
